node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Sheleana Aiyana on August 13, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Just like you cannot rush a flower to bloom before it is time. you cannot rush yourself through grief or transformation. Surrender the timeline, and in that space, truth will find its way to you There is medicine in your process that will reveal itself in time. @SheleanaAiyana'.

node.text:
We do not control the seasons of this earth and we cannot control the seasons of our lives either.

Our power is not in attempting to manipulate the timeline, rush a transformation or in trying to extract the lessons as fast as possible.

Our power is found in the moments of deep surrender - opening to nothingness and making room for the medicine to do its work.

These things take time, grief is transformative on its own timeline. Taking time to let truth find its way to you is the medicine.

Resting when you want to run is the medicine. Trusting when you want to resist is the medicine.

It’s ok to move slowly, it’s ok not to know. It’s ok to just be. Nothing lasts forever, and for now, this is your process.

🌿 @sheleanaaiyana

node.text:
This place is not new
But it never gets old
These trees never move
but each time I come
they move me, in one way
or another

These trees do not speak aloud,
But if they had words 
they would tell me I am safe here
they have seen broken spirits and sad hearts pass through them quietly
seeking solace and refuge

They have watched lovers pass through
hand in hand
heads in the clouds
bodies thirsty

they have watched lonely souls 
walk slowly, looking up to the sky
with a wanting in their eyes

oh what they have seen 
for generations, standing tall
giving shade, never to move, only to sway and gently bend,
the roots run deep, they’ve seen it all

they have watched children run wildly, mothers trailing behind
they have watched the same people 
day by day, passing through
same trail, different story, new memories

they have watched hearts come in broken
leaving renewed
they have seen thousands of winters, thousands of springs
they have been birthing grounds, and a place of death and dying
over and over, their cycles repeat

this place is not new
but it is never the same
the trees do not speak aloud
but if they had words
they would tell me I am doing just fine
that in some ways, we are the same
transforming over, and over, and over
again.

🌿 @sheleanaaiyana - Written in 2015 as I emerged from a deep cocoon of grief. My rituals were days wandering the forest, cold river dips, spring water runs and laying on the earth. The trees, plants, flowers and waters held me through it. I met my husband 3 months after this I wrote this passage.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Sheleana Aiyana on July 22, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Should you really be "getting back out there" in the dating world? Let go ofthe of the family societal pressure to find someone and trust that your body will let you know when you're ready to open your heart again. @SheleanaAiyana'.

node.text:
Should you really be “getting back out there” in the dating world? I hear it all the time… “I should get back out there” they tell me, but I just feel dread.

When our hearts are heavy and a loss has yet to run it’s course, why do we feel like we need to speed up the process?

Family and friends tell us we should. But the only messenger who can tell you when it’s time is the voice within you.

It’s ok to take your time, you don’t need to date until you’re ready and yes even 2+ years is allowed.

Sometimes the medicine of grief and healing needs all of us, and when this is our reality we may actually do harm by forcing ourselves out before we are ready.

When our confidence has not yet returned, when our bodies are still holding tightly onto trauma - it shows. In our body, in our energy, in how we make eye contact (or don’t) and the people who will be drawn to us when we are low and vulnerable may very well not be the safest either.

Connect to the elements and let nature be your teacher. Immerse your body in water and let it cleanse your sorrows. Plant your feed firmly in the earth and let the dirt between your toes remind you that you are home.

You have kinship in the plants and the trees. Notice them when you walk, let their energy hold you in this process of transformation.

Don’t rush yourself. You are not alone and you will not be left behind if you take this time for you. Seasons will shift and change and that’s ok. Let this time be what it needs to be.

🌿@sheleanaaiyana

The very fabric of your being is interwoven with the energy of the land beneath your feet and the sky above. You are the plants and the trees, the forests and the rivers. When you feel lost and alone, let the earth hold you. You are not separate from love, love is all that you are.'.

Photo by Sheleana Aiyana on July 14, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'forever. don't want the honeymoon phase want the depth that can only come from having climbed tall mountains and walked the low valleys together. don't want the butterflies of excitement and lust. want the peace of knowing a true and medicinal kind of love One where we heal our past and make way for a better future because of who we inspire each other to be. @SheleanaAiyana Aiyana'.

node.text:
When I was a younger woman, relationships were nothing more than a facet of consumption to me. I craved and crafted the honeymoon phase - the rushes of dopamine, the butterflies, thinking and fantasizing of The One - whoever they happened to be at this juncture.

When the honeymoon phase would end I’d be left with a hollow feeling in my belly along with confusion as to why is was ending. What’s wrong with me, I thought, why can’t I make this feeling last?

Only to realize that what I was experiencing was an old wound from childhood that had me addicted to the false sense of being someone’s entire world - it was my inner-child that needed the intensity of being chosen.

So much of our culture is enveloped in the false narrative that “true love” must feel like tsunami of feels forever, and so we often confuse the transition from new love to mature love for being broken.

The Honeymoon phase in many ways can be a bit of a selfish time - and it’s a beautiful phase.

One where you carve out extra time for this new person and the enamour is high. For a time, the focus is on exploration and discovery - it’s all very fresh and exciting!

But mature love doesn’t mean that you’ll no longer feel attracted to your partner or have moments of intensity or deep passion - it means that when you have those experiences, they’re more rooted.

Mature love is medicinal - it has had time to work in you both and alchemize the unique ingredients you’ve each brought to the partnership.

I don't want the honeymoon phase forever. I want the depth that can only come from having climbed tall mountains and walked the low valleys together.

I don't want the butterflies of excitement and lust, I want the peace of knowing a true and medicinal kind of love.

One where we heal our past and make way for a better future because of who we inspire each other to be.

The kind of love that is calm and devoted, playful and energizing.

The kind of love that does not consume all of the energy between us like a vacuum but serves as a power grid to redistribute our gifts throughout our community and world - a love that gives us the energy to serve higher.

🌿 @sheleanaaiyana

node.text:
My goodness how I adore this man. Just look at that sweet face 🥰 

Today marks 2 years of marriage and 6 years with this beautiful human being.

Ben @evolvingman - Thank you for the way you take care of me, and our community. 

Thank you for how you show up when times are tough, and for constantly leaning back into connection with me when we fall out of practice and let the busyness of life take over.

Thank you for being so clear on your direction and unwavering in your commitment. 

And thank you for being a master guide, planner, leader - one of the things I love about being with you is that when we're traveling (or going just about anywhere) I am so surrendered that I usually have no idea where I am! I've spent my entire life leading, and you invite me to relax.

You are my opposite in so many ways and I am constantly learning from you.

Thank you for inviting my feminine wisdom, visions and insights and valuing my perspective even when it's a challenge, especially when it's a challenge.

Devoted to continuing our path of learning together and becoming the best team we can be.

It’s not always easy, but it’s always worth it. 

In harmony and love 🌊🌿💕

May be an image of text that says 'For those of us who had a painful or traumatic childhood, moving deeper into commitment or starting a family can bring up a lot of fear. Making a choice to break the cycle is the most courageous thing you could ever do. Don't let your past prevent you from having a beautiful future. @SheleanaAiyana'.

node.text:
This message today is as much for me as it is for you 🌿 when we’ve come from pain and dysfunction, stepping deeper into relationship or thinking about creating a family can bring up a lot.

What if I don’t know how to be in relationship?
.
What if I don’t know how to be a good parent because I wasn’t parented?
.
What if I repeat the patterns of my family history and ruin it all?
.
The truth? Being human is hard sometimes. We are all going to make mistakes. No one does it perfectly. But the very fact that you are even asking these questions is a testament to how much you care.

The fact that you are worried about repeating your history says it all - that awareness means you are already breaking the cycle.

There is nothing more beautiful or courageous than witnessing people choose to open their hearts and let love in when their entire history has told them it isn’t safe to do so.

Deep bows to each and every one of you who choose to take the journey toward healing in love in all its forms.

🌿 @sheleanaaiyana

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Sheleana Aiyana on June 13, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'All relationships go through phases and seasons. No relationship stays in the honeymoon phase or the season of spring/summer forever. Let's normalize growing through the seasons together and rising in love @SheleanaAiyana Aiyana'.

node.text:
The truth about why long-term relationships fizzle out and die. 🥀

Our exposure to relationship is often through media that portrays one phase + season of relationship: honeymoon spring. 🌿🌸

Honeymoon phase / spring cycle of relationship is what we are exposed to the most - newness, budding with fresh energy, passion, mystery (we don’t know each other’s depths yet), a whole beautiful future ahead.

We aren’t culturally prepared for the cycles that long-term relationship bring.

Long-term relationships go through phases and cycles just like every other living being on the planet.

And when fall and winter hit, we often feel defeated, lost and confused. Where did the love go? Why is the passion gone? I guess we’ve just fallen out of love.

But this is one of the vital errors couples make... to let the relationship end when the seasons are shifting rather than embracing change consciously and letting go of what needs to die to make space for new energy to birth in the relationship.

Relationships are meant to shift, change, shed, die and rebirth. What we need to normalize is a cultural expectation that fall and winter will come, and there’s nothing wrong when it does.

Resentment kills relationships faster than anything, a commitment to radical honesty and willingness to ride the waves is the antidote.

Let your partnership grow - don’t abandon it the moment the seasons shift. There is depth, truth, and mystery to uncover when the darkness comes.

🌿 @sheleanaaiyana
